shared_text:
AIM Independent Living Center
September 2 at 3:47 PM ·

AIM will operate a community learning pod this school year for students in the Corning-Painted Post School District who are attending classes remotely due to COVID-19.

The learning pod will be located at 254 E. First St., Corning, the former Southern Tier Pediatrics building which is owned by AIM. Our staff will provide supervision and technical support while students learn remotely from C-PP teachers.

The learning pod will operate from 8 a.m.-3 p.m. weekdays beginning Monday, Sept. 14. To participate, students must live in the C-PP district and be in grades 1-5. The pod will be limited to 10 students, with appropriate health measures in place. The cost is $35 per day per student.

For more information or to register, contact Joe Coffey at jcoffey@aimcil.com or (607) 962-8225, ext. 155.

post_text:
Lisa Caracci, Executive Director for the Steuben County Habitat for Humanity and William Pierce, Asst. Supt. for School Operations are pictured with one of the 8,000 masks that were recently donated by Habitat for Humanity to the Corning-Painted Post Area School District.

The Assistant Superintendent for School Operations, William Pierce stated, “This is a wonderful example of a partnership with one of our community programs that we truly value, and that resonates across staff and students in our school district. We are grateful for the work of Habitat for Humanity of Steuben County, and the generous donation of 8,000 masks that will play a tremendous role in our reopening in September.”

Class of 2021 - Seniors and Families:

Free senior yearbook portrait sessions are scheduled for next week, August 10-14 — please review this important information from the Tesserae yearbook staff at CPPHS.

Seniors must confirm their appointment slot with the information on the postcard that came in the mail earlier this week; if you cannot find or do not have a postcard, call 716-633-4466 and press 5.

EDIT: Parents needing to find their student's appointment time have found it easier to go to www.PrestigePortraits.com, and select "Corning, NY," then enter their student's name — the website will then look up your appointment time.

From Mr. Simons: "Seniors & parents - due to uncertainty with our schedule, we ask that you please participate in these FREE sessions next week so we can include all of our seniors in the 2021 yearbook!! Sessions are free. Please note that you must wear a mask the entire time you are in CPPHS, except when you're seated for the portrait. Please call Prestige at the number provided with questions about your appointment."

shared_text:
Corning Hawks
July 23 at 2:53 PM ·

Corning Hawks! If you need a physical for athletics, we have a date for you!

Physicals will take place at the high school on August 6th. Please call the nurse at 654-2782 or 654-2784 to set up an appointment. If you need to you can leave a message and they will return your call.

Due to COVID-19 we have some procedures involved in our physicals. Please see below:

1) August 6th from 8 am -12 pm at the high school.
2) Enter through the main doors at the front of the building.
3) Only students will be allowed to enter the building - parents will be asked to wait outside or in their cars.
4) Students must wear a mask, at all times, unless otherwise instructed during the physical.
5) Students will have their temperatures taken and will complete a 4 question screening questionnaire before entering the building.
6) Students will be expected to follow all social distancing guidelines and school protocols explained to them upon arrival.

post_text:
Carder 5th Grader’s Creative Video Project Tells the Story of the Flood of 1972

During Phase 2 of Virtual ELA Learning, each 5th grader was assigned to complete a "Natural Disaster" project. Carder 5th grade teacher Mrs. Kimberly Karam said, “For his research topic, Jude Maxim chose the Corning Flood of 1972. He has a personal connection to the flood which is a flood marker visible on one of the columns of his front porch. Jude wrote the script and his older brothers helped turn it into a video.”

Thank you to Jude, his family and Mrs. Karam for sharing this project.

You can watch his project on YouTube at this link:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dR5MSzj3AsY&feature=youtu.be

shared_text:
Corning Hawks
April 29 at 4:51 PM ·

Corning Hawks: This Friday night, May 1st, the Corning Memorial Stadium will again have the lights on! We will light up the stadium from 8:20 to 8:40 pm. We want to honor all our students, parents and staff who are currently missing all the activities and community events that the school provides. We want everyone to know we are thinking about them, we miss them, we love them and we are all anxious for their return. In light of the current conditions we must follow all social distancing rules to help in this endeavor: we will not allow congregating on Corning-Painted Post High School grounds. We advise that you drive by the stadium or drive over the bridge to view the stadium. Do not congregate together. Remember to follow all social distancing rules and to wear your mask when in public, no matter where you are.

Drive by and celebrate our students, parents and staff as we light our stadium!

Thank your Mr. Jeremy Austin for the incredible pictures!

post_text: Attention Erwin Valley students - Principal Kate Merrill asked us to share this information!
shared_text:
LPC Little League
April 15 at 7:08 PM ·

In an effort to support students in our community, LPC has installed a WiFi hotspot at our fields. We realize that many students in the Lindley area do not have reliable access to the internet. Wifi can be accessed from the parking lot nearest the main entrance. You will need to message us through this FB page or send us an email, at lpclittleleague@gmail.com, to request the password. This will enable us to keep a count on how many students are using the service. Please follow the guidelines attached in this post. Anyone wishing to make a monetary donation to help cover the cost can do so by sending us a message or email. Stay safe everyone and hopefully we will see you soon!
text:
Attention Erwin Valley students - Principal Kate Merrill asked us to share this information!

April 15 at 7:08 PM ·

In an effort to support students in our community, LPC has installed a WiFi hotspot at our fields. We realize that many students in the Lindley area do not have reliable access to the internet. Wifi can be accessed from the parking lot nearest the main entrance. You will need to message us through this FB page or send us an email, at lpclittleleague@gmail.com, to request the password. This will enable us to keep a count on how many students are using the service. Please follow the guidelines attached in this post. Anyone wishing to make a monetary donation to help cover the cost can do so by sending us a message or email. Stay safe everyone and hopefully we will see you soon!

EDITED with UPDATED TIMES: Message from Mr. Kimble, MS Executive Principal:

It was brought to my attention that there are two different dates circulating about the drop off plan for work from Phase 1. This message is for anyone who did not come in Tuesday to pick up work.

Phase 1 drop off can be done today, Wednesday, April 15, until 4 pm or tomorrow, Thursday, April 16 from 9 am-4 pm. There are 3 large totes in front of The Main Entrance with a corresponding grade level on them. Place your Phase 1 work in the correct grade level tote. Please be sure that the work is secured together with a paper clip or in a large envelope.

I apologize for the confusion that was created with the two different dates being shared.

Richard A Kimble
Executive Principal
C-PP Middle School

post_text:
Hi Scholar-Roos!

School Counselor Ms. Bastion here, with my cat Coe, saying hi and that I miss you!

This week featured Pets or Peeps day for our second spirit week. I hope you enjoyed spending time with your pets and peeps at home!

Spending time with pets and people, such as your parents and siblings, is a good way to cope with everything going on. It helps calm us down to pet an animal (or a stuffed animal if you don’t have a pet), spend time with people, and talk about our feelings. https://vimeo.com/403320210
